## 8. The Chinese Remainder Theorem (ring edition)

The **Chinese Remainder Theorem** (CRT) says that if `m` and `n` are coprime, then `ℤ/(mn) ≅ ℤ/m × ℤ/n` as rings. We can solve systems of congruences uniquely.

---

### 8.1 Solving x ≡ 2 (mod 3), x ≡ 3 (mod 5)

```scheme
(define system (list (list 2 3) (list 3 5)))

(define solution (nt/crt system))

solution
```
[VISUAL: prints `8` — the unique solution modulo `15`]
<!-- BUILD: run and verify CRT solution -->

Check: `8 ≡ 2 (mod 3)` and `8 ≡ 3 (mod 5)`.

---

### 8.2 Solving a three-modulus system

```scheme
(define system (list (list 1 3) (list 2 5) (list 3 7)))

(define solution (nt/crt system))

solution
```
[VISUAL: prints `52` — the unique solution modulo `105`]
<!-- BUILD: run and verify multi-modulus CRT -->

---

### 8.3 Ring isomorphism via CRT

The ring `ℤ/15` is isomorphic to `ℤ/3 × ℤ/5`. An element `x (mod 15)` corresponds to the pair `(x mod 3, x mod 5)`.

```scheme
(define x 8)

(define pair (list (nt/mod x 3) (nt/mod x 5)))

pair
```
[VISUAL: prints `(2 3)` — the image of `8` in ℤ/3 × ℤ/5]
<!-- BUILD: run and verify isomorphism map -->

---

## 9. Polynomial rings over ℤ/p

Working in `(ℤ/p)[x]` combines modular arithmetic and polynomial algebra. This is the foundation of many cryptographic schemes.

---

### 9.1 Adding polynomials over ℤ/3

```scheme
(define mod3
  (lambda (coeffs)
    (map (lambda (c) (nt/mod c 3)) coeffs)))

(define p1 (sym/poly 'x (list 2 1 2)))
(define p2 (sym/poly 'x (list 1 2 1)))

(define sum (sym/add p1 p2))
(define sum-mod3 (sym/poly 'x (mod3 (map (lambda (i) (sym/coeff sum i)) (list 0 1 2)))))

sum-mod3
```
[VISUAL: prints the polynomial with coefficients reduced modulo 3]
<!-- BUILD: run and display polynomial over ℤ/3 -->

---

### 9.2 Multiplying polynomials over ℤ/5

```scheme
(define mod5
  (lambda (coeffs)
    (map (lambda (c) (nt/mod c 5)) coeffs)))

(define p1 (sym/poly 'x (list 3 1)))
(define p2 (sym/poly 'x (list 2 1)))

(define prod (sym/mul p1 p2))
(define prod-mod5 (sym/poly 'x (mod5 (map (lambda (i) (sym/coeff prod i)) (list 0 1 2)))))

prod-mod5
```
[VISUAL: prints `(1 0 1)` — representing `1 + x²` over ℤ/5, since `(3 + 2) = 0` and `(3·1 + 1·2) = 0` (mod 5)]
<!-- BUILD: run and display polynomial multiplication over finite field -->

