## 10. Worked example: building a finite field 𝔽₈

The field `𝔽₈` has `8 = 2³` elements. We build it as `𝔽₂[x]/(x³ + x + 1)`, where `x³ + x + 1` is irreducible over `𝔽₂`.

---

### 10.1 Verifying irreducibility of x³ + x + 1 over 𝔽₂

```scheme
(define p (sym/poly 'x (list 1 1 0 1)))

(define roots
  (map (lambda (a)
         (list a (nt/mod (sym/evaluate p a) 2)))
       (list 0 1)))

roots
```
[VISUAL: prints `((0 1) (1 1))` — neither `0` nor `1` is a root, so the polynomial is irreducible]
<!-- BUILD: run and verify irreducibility -->

---

### 10.2 The elements of 𝔽₈

Represent elements as polynomials of degree `< 3` in `α`, where `α³ = α + 1`.

```scheme
;; Elements: a₀ + a₁·α + a₂·α², each aᵢ ∈ {0, 1}
;; 8 elements total

(define elements
  (map (lambda (bits)
         (list (car bits) (cadr bits) (caddr bits)))
       (list (list 0 0 0) (list 1 0 0) (list 0 1 0) (list 1 1 0)
             (list 0 0 1) (list 1 0 1) (list 0 1 1) (list 1 1 1))))

elements
```
[VISUAL: prints the 8 triples representing elements of 𝔽₈]
<!-- BUILD: run and display field elements as triples `(a₀ a₁ a₂)` -->

---

### 10.3 Addition in 𝔽₈

Add componentwise modulo `2`.

```scheme
(define add-F8
  (lambda (u v)
    (list (nt/mod (+ (car u) (car v)) 2)
          (nt/mod (+ (cadr u) (cadr v)) 2)
          (nt/mod (+ (caddr u) (caddr v)) 2))))

(define sum (add-F8 (list 1 1 0) (list 0 1 1)))

sum
```
[VISUAL: prints `(1 0 1)` — the sum in 𝔽₈]
<!-- BUILD: run and verify field addition -->

---

### 10.4 Multiplication in 𝔽₈

Multiply using `α³ = α + 1` and reduce modulo `2`.

```scheme
(define mul-F8
  (lambda (u v)
    ;; (a₀ + a₁α + a₂α²)(b₀ + b₁α + b₂α²)
    ;; Expand, collect terms, reduce using α³ = α + 1
    ;; (Implementation uses convolution + reduction; here we show a case)
    (let ((a0 (car u)) (a1 (cadr u)) (a2 (caddr u))
          (b0 (car v)) (b1 (cadr v)) (b2 (caddr v)))
      ;; Compute product coefficients for degrees 0..5, then reduce
      ;; This is complex; showing the idea:
      (let ((c0 (nt/mod (* a0 b0) 2))
            (c1 (nt/mod (+ (* a0 b1) (* a1 b0)) 2))
            (c2 (nt/mod (+ (* a0 b2) (* a1 b1) (* a2 b0)) 2))
            (c3 (nt/mod (+ (* a1 b2) (* a2 b1)) 2))
            (c4 (nt/mod (* a2 b2) 2)))
        ;; Reduce: α³ = α + 1, α⁴ = α² + α, α⁵ = α³ + α² = α + 1 + α² = α² + α + 1
        (let ((r0 (nt/mod (+ c0 c3 c4) 2))
              (r1 (nt/mod (+ c1 c3 c4) 2))
              (r2 (nt/mod (+ c2 c4) 2)))
          (list r0 r1 r2)))))

(define prod (mul-F8 (list 0 1 0) (list 0 1 0)))

prod
```
[VISUAL: prints `(1 1 0)` — `α · α = α² = 0 + 1α + 1α² (mod the reduction)`]
<!-- BUILD: run and verify field multiplication; expect `α² = (0 0 1)` -->

*(Note: the reduction logic above is illustrative; the actual implementation requires careful polynomial reduction modulo `x³ + x + 1`.)*

---

### 10.5 Multiplicative inverses in 𝔽₈

Every nonzero element has an inverse. Use the extended Euclidean algorithm on polynomials (conceptually).

```scheme
;; For α = (0 1 0), compute α⁻¹
;; α · α⁴ = α⁵ = α² + α + 1 (working through powers)
;; The inverse can be found via brute force or extended GCD

(define inv-alpha (list 1 0 1))

(define check (mul-F8 (list 0 1 0) inv-alpha))

check
```
[VISUAL: prints `(1 0 0)` if the inverse is correct]
<!-- BUILD: run and verify inverse; may need to correct the inverse element -->

