## 11. Characteristic and prime fields

A field of **characteristic** `p` (prime) contains a copy of `𝔽ₚ` as its **prime subfield**. Every finite field has prime-power order `pⁿ` and characteristic `p`.

---

### 11.1 The characteristic of ℚ, ℝ, ℂ

```scheme
;; The characteristic is 0 (no finite sum of 1's equals 0)

(define char-Q 0)

char-Q
```
[VISUAL: prints `0` — characteristic of the rationals]
<!-- BUILD: display the concept -->

---

### 11.2 The characteristic of 𝔽₈

```scheme
(define char-F8 2)

char-F8
```
[VISUAL: prints `2` — since 𝔽₈ is built over 𝔽₂]
<!-- BUILD: display the characteristic -->

---

## 12. Frobenius endomorphism

In a field of characteristic `p`, the **Frobenius map** `φ(x) = xᵖ` is an automorphism. It fixes the prime subfield and permutes the other elements.

---

### 12.1 Frobenius in 𝔽₅

```scheme
(define p 5)

(define frob
  (map (lambda (a)
         (list a (nt/mod-pow a p p)))
       (list 0 1 2 3 4)))

frob
```
[VISUAL: prints `((0 0) (1 1) (2 2) (3 3) (4 4))` — the Frobenius fixes every element in 𝔽₅]
<!-- BUILD: run and verify Frobenius map -->

In the prime field, `xᵖ = x` for all `x` (Fermat's Little Theorem).

---

### 12.2 Frobenius in 𝔽₄

In `𝔽₄ = 𝔽₂[α]/(α² + α + 1)`, the Frobenius map `φ(x) = x²` permutes the non-prime-field elements.

```scheme
;; Elements: 0, 1, α, 1+α
;; φ(α) = α² = α + 1 (from α² + α + 1 = 0)
;; φ(1+α) = (1+α)² = 1 + α² = 1 + (α + 1) = α

(define frob-F4
  (list (list 0 0) (list 1 1) (list 'alpha '(1+alpha)) (list '(1+alpha) 'alpha)))

frob-F4
```
[VISUAL: prints the Frobenius action on 𝔽₄ elements]
<!-- BUILD: display the permutation conceptually -->

---

## 13. Structure tables

A **structure table** (Cayley table) shows the result of a binary operation on every pair of elements. For groups, rings, and fields, these tables reveal commutativity, inverses, and closure.

---

### 13.1 Addition table for ℤ/4

```scheme
(define n 4)

(define add-table
  (map (lambda (a)
         (map (lambda (b)
                (nt/mod (+ a b) n))
              (list 0 1 2 3)))
       (list 0 1 2 3)))

add-table
```
[VISUAL: prints a 4×4 table showing addition modulo 4]
<!-- BUILD: run and render as a grid/table -->

---

### 13.2 Multiplication table for (ℤ/7)×

```scheme
(define p 7)
(define units (alg/zn-units p))

(define mul-table
  (map (lambda (a)
         (map (lambda (b)
                (nt/mod (* a b) p))
              units))
       units))

mul-table
```
[VISUAL: prints a 6×6 table showing multiplication of units modulo 7]
<!-- BUILD: run and render as a grid/table; each row is a permutation -->

---

### 13.3 Multiplication table for 𝔽₄

```scheme
;; Elements: 0, 1, α, 1+α (as defined earlier)
;; Build the full 4×4 multiplication table using mul-F4

(define elements (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 0 1) (list 1 1)))

(define mul-table-F4
  (map (lambda (a)
         (map (lambda (b)
                (mul-F4 a b))
              elements))
       elements))

mul-table-F4
```
[VISUAL: prints a 4×4 nested list showing the multiplication table of 𝔽₄]
<!-- BUILD: run and render as a labeled grid showing field multiplication -->

